<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Blockcode tag]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=4311&amp;p=6974#p6974"><![CDATA[
Those are elements, not tags. A tag is the starting or ending portion of an element therefore 99.9% of the time it is professional to refer to these as elements. The only condition I can think of that it would be professional to refer to a tag is if you're referring to self-closing elements (e.g. do I need a closing tag for the br or img elements?).<br /><br />Just apply the CSS white-space property as you see fit. Here is a slimmed down example from my website of how I handle the code element's formatting...<br /><br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: </dt><dd><code>code {white-space: pre;}<br />div code {display: block;}<br />div p code, div span code, li code {display: inline;}</code></dd></dl><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=47">JAB Creations</a> — Thu Mar 31, 2011 8:58 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
